            <seg xml:id="C19_app60-#fThomas_end"/>
               <seg xml:id="C19_app60-#fThomas_start"/>
            <seg xml:id="C19_app60-#fThomas_end"/>
               <seg xml:id="C19_app60-#fThomas_start"/>up in the precious charge; how the mind of youth expanded and gained
            knowledge; of brother, sister, and all the various relationships which bind one human
            being to another in mutual bonds.&lt;p
            loc="novel1_letter4_chapter12_p353__End"/&gt;&lt;p
            loc="novel1_letter4_chapter12_p354__Start"/&gt;“But where were my friends and relations?
            No father had watched my infant days, no mother had blessed me with smiles and caresses;
            or if they had, all my past life was now a blot, a blind vacancy in which I
            distinguished nothing. From my earliest remembrance I had been as I then was in height
            and proportion. I had never yet seen a being resembling me, or who claimed any
            intercourse with me. What was I? The question again recurred, to be answered only with
            groans.&lt;p loc="novel1_letter4_chapter12_p354__End"/&gt;&lt;p
            loc="novel1_letter4_chapter12_p355__Start"/&gt;“I will soon explain to what these
            feelings tended; but allow me now to return to the cottagers, whose story excited in me
            such various feelings of indignation, delight, and wonder, but which all terminated in
            additional love and reverence for my protectors (for so I loved, in an innocent, half
            painful self-deceit, to call them).&lt;p
            loc="novel1_letter4_chapter12_p355__End"/&gt;&lt;milestone n="12" type="end"
